Homework 1

13 04 2022

In this homework, we are expected to select at least 3 different measures of interest from EVDS of Central Bank of Turkey and at least 1 relevant search keyword from Google Trends. The purpose of the homework is to get used to data manipulation and visualization of time series objects and interpret correlations among different measures of interest.

Introduction

As a small individual investor, I started to invest in Borsa Istanbul approximately at the beginning of 2020. Since then, price of the XU100 index went up and down with an increasing trend as well as the volume in the market. In the mean time, USD Dollar/TRY exchange rate increased, too. Therefore, I wondered if there is any correlation between these 3 measeures of interest. My intiution tells me that XU100 price is highly correlated with USD Dollar/TRY exchange rate because they move almost always accordingly. On the other hand, the relation between Dollar rate and XU100 volume is harder to predict since the volume is very volatile lately. Lastly, I somehow sense that as XU100 price goes up, XU100 volume increase similarly.

The other part of the homework is about relevant Google Trends search keywords. I chose Borsa term to examine the relation between the interests of people for stock market and stock prices or market volume. Second keyword is Dolar. My aim is to find the relation between search volume of Dolar in google trends data and USD Dollar/TRY exchange rate.

Shortly, my research questions are:

  • Are the BIST100 Price and Volume correlated with Dollar Rate or each other?

  • Are Google Trends search volumes for Dolar and Borsa keywords correlated with Dollar Rate, BIST100 Price and Volume?

Letâs examine the questions via visualizations and correlations tests.

Analaysis

Data Manipulation and Visualization

Firstly, I picked the BIST100 Prices, BIST100 Volume and Dollar Rate data from Electronic Data Delivery System (EVDS) of Central Bank of Turkey. Secondly, Dolar Search and Borsa Search data are taken from Google Trends.

autoplot(evds_ts[,"BIST100Price"], size=1) +

3. Time Plot of Dollar Rate

autoplot(evds_ts[,"DollarRate"], size=1) + 
  geom_smooth(fill = NA, color="orange", size = 1) +

When we look at each of the 3 time plots, we can see the similarity in general. Here is some interpretations:

  • Especially, BIST100 Price and Dollar Rate plots are very alike in terms of trends and movements except for BIST100 Price is more volatile.

  • Trend of the BIST100 Price seems linear until 2019 and after that time becomes nonlinear.

  • Trend of Dollar Rate seems nonlinear all the time between 2010 and 2022.

  • On the other hand, BIST100 Volume plot seems flat until 2017 (no trend), after that time the volume started to increase significantly similar to other 2 plots.

  • BIST100 Volume has the highest volatility and is exposed huge fall at 2021 different from other measures.

  • Although there are fluctuations on the each plot during positive trend, it is hard to interpret about seasonalities since there is no obvious pattern.

Histograms and Box Plots of EVDS Data

We can interpret about frequency distributions via histograms. We graph histograms for each year, thus we can interpret about each year seperately.

Boxplots allow us to interpret data from different perspective. We have 5 number summary of the data, thus we can talk about characteristics of the data and especially about outliers.

1. Histogram and Box Plot of BIST100 Price

ggplot(data = evds_data, aes(x=BIST100Price)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 8, alpha = 0.3, aes(color = Year, fill = Year)) +
  facet_wrap(Year~.,scales = "free",ncol = 5) +
  labs(title = "Histograms of BIST100 Prices for Years 2010-2022",
       x = "BIST100 Price",
       y = "Frequency") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=60, hjust=1.5, vjust = 1.5))

  • Roughly, we can say that BIST100 Prices increase throughout years.
  • Price intervals between 2010-2019 are around 200-300 TRY, which are relatively small compared to 2020-2022 which have intervals more than 600 TRY.
  • Frequency distributions of years are all different. Some years have distribution similar to normal, some are right-skewed and some are left-skewed. Thus, it is hard to interpret about distributions in general.
ggplot(data = evds_data, aes(x=Year, y=BIST100Price)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(y=BIST100Price, fill = Year)) +
  labs(title = "Boxplots of BIST100 Prices for Years 2010-2022",
       x = "Years",
       y = "BIST100 Prices")

Box plot of BIST100 Prices for each year confirms our comments on histogram. Additionaly:

  • In 2021, there are many outliers in the price that make it difficult to interpret.
  • It is very obvious that, increment in the price is greater after 2020.

Correlations

After the interpretation via visualization, Pearsonâs product-moment correlation tests can be applied to check our research questions. The results of this test show us the soundness and the direction of the relationship between two measures of interest. Test results vary between -1 and . -1 indicates perfect negative relationship which means as one increase the other decrease. 1 indicates perfect positive relationship which means two variables move together. Lastly, 0 indicates no relationship.

Now letâs focus on the relationships between our EVDS data and Google Trends data:

Correlation between BIST100 Price and Dollar Rate

cor.test(x = evds_data$BIST100Price, y = evds_data$DollarRate, 
         method = "pearson", alternative = "greater")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  evds_data$BIST100Price and evds_data$DollarRate
## t = 64.935, df = 640, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9226672 1.0000000
## sample estimates:
##      cor 
## 0.931782

We can say that there is a strong correlation between Dolar Rate and BIST100 Price which confirms our early comments.

Correlation Plot

We can see the results of whole correlation test visually via correlation plot.

Before doing it, we need to create monthly time series to match all EVDS data and Google Trends data

evds_monthly_data_ts <- cbind(ts(evds_monthly_data[-c(1,5)], start = 2010, frequency = 12), 
                              ts(gt_dolar_data$DolarSearch, start = 2010, frequency = 12),
                              ts(gt_borsa_data$BorsaSearch, start = 2010, frequency = 12))
colnames(evds_monthly_data_ts) <- c("BIST100 Price", "BIST100 Volume", "Dollar Rate", 
                                    "GT Dolar Search", "GT Borsa Search")

Now, we can draw correlation plot:

corrplot.mixed(cor(evds_monthly_data_ts, use="pairwise.complete.obs"), 
               tl.col="black", tl.pos = "lt")

This is the visual representation of all correlations between measures of interest.

Scatter Plots

Lastly, we can use scatter plots to extend our understanding on correlations.

Scatter Plots of EVDS Data

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(x = evds_data$BIST100Price,y = evds_data$DollarRate,
     main = "BIST100 Price vs. Dollar Rate",
     xlab = "BIST100 Price", ylab = "Dollar Rate")
plot(x = evds_data$BIST100Volume,y = evds_data$DollarRate,
     main = "BIST100 Volume vs. Dollar Rate",
     xlab = "BIST100 Volume", ylab = "DollarRate")
plot(x = evds_data$BIST100Price,y = evds_data$BIST100Volume,
     main = "BIST100 Price vs. BIST100 Volume",
     xlab = "BIST100 Price", ylab = "BIST100 Volume)")

Between EVDS data, we can easily say that the strongest correlation is between BIST100 Price and Dollar Rate. Thanks to scatter plot, we can interpret more about the relation. Firstly, the relation between them seems linear. Moreover, we can mention about the presence of some serial dependence. The relation between Dollar Rate and BIST100 Volume seems linear when dollar rate is betwen 2-6. After that, as dollar rate increases, volume scattered a lot which violates the constant variance assumption. Lastly, the relation between BIST100 Price and BIST100 Volume seems nonlinear and variance increases as price increases, which violation of constant variance assumption similar to previous relation I mentioned.

Scatter Plots of EVDS Data vs.Â Google Trends Data

par(mfrow=c(1,3))

Firstly, as a consequence of high correlation test results, Dolar Search and Dollar Rate seems increase accordingly in a linear way. However, as dolar rate exceeds 10, we can see a lot of outlier data points which somehow sabotage the relation. The relation between BIST100 Volume and Borsa Search seems better than the relation between BIST100 Price and Borsa Search. Volume and search relation seems nonlinear and violates the constant variance assumption when the volume in the market exceeds 10 billion TRY. Relation between price and search seems linear up to price of 1200. After that point, data scatters a lot and ruins the correlation.

Conclusion

To sum up, the correlations between Dollar Rate, BIST100 Price and BIST100 Volume are all very high and significant. Especially, BIST100 Price moves accordingly to Dollar Rate. Other than that, Google Trends Dolar Search has a strong correlation with the Dolar Rate. Relation between Borsa Search and BIST100 Price or BIST100 Volume is not strong as the relation between dolar search and rate. To reveal the relations between measures of interest fully, further investigations are necessary. However, I can proudly say that they have some strong relations as I suspected.
